        "comments": [
          {
            "text": "This game was played on chess.com between Magnus Carlsen and Daniel Naroditsky. \n\nLet's use the 4 criteria of evaluating positions.\n\nMaterial is equal. \n\nThe White king is safer than Black's. There's a pawn on h5 undermining the g6-hook, and h6 and f6 are weak around the king. \n\nWhite's pieces are better: the rook is on e1, the knight on e4. The Black bishop on h8 bites on granite on d4, and Black still has to develop the light-squared bishop.\n\nWhite has a +2 advantage according to the engine.",
            "arrows": {
              "threats": [],
              "opportunities": []
            },
            "highlights": null
          },
          {
            "text": "White in fact has a wide variety of moves he could play and still be better.\n\nHe could develop the queen to f3. He could trade on g6. He could play Bg5, probing the f6 weakness. Or the bishop could go to h6, attacking the rook. Ba3 was played in the game.\n\nHook: a hook is a pawn in a position that can be attacked, literally \"hooked onto\" with another one of your pawns to open up a file.",
            "arrows": {
